’The State Department of Education is funding free mobile hotspots for the fall 2020 semester for qualifying students from Marlboro County School District. . Only one hot spot per address is allowable. Eligibility for a hot spot is as follows:
1. At least one child in the home is enrolled as a student in Marlboro County School District.
2. Permanent wireless access is not available in the home. Cellular phone hotspots are not considered permanent.
3. The gross household income must be at or below the income levels listed in the application chart.
Application deadline is September 30, 2020.

post_text: From Dr. Gregory A. McCord, Superintendent: "Today we were recognized by the Marlboro County Chamber of Commerce as an organization! This is a great accomplishment for our team! All of Marlboro County School District employees are a part of this team! Every staff member adds value to our mission and our vision! I thank you for your service and for allowing me to serve in this great district!" #345Marlboro

post_text:
You should have been notified by your school which day your child will attend school during LEAP Week, August 24-28. If you have not received this information, call the school at your earliest convenience.

In this world of uncertainty, we have been forced to make some tough decisions as we transition back into the school setting. In an effort to keep our students and our staff safe, starting August 24th, only the child will be allowed into the school. We will have staff available at the entrance to escort/direct your child to his/her classroom. We understand this is not the ideal situation and we wish we didn't have to put these procedures into practice, but due to the spread of COVID-19, we do not want to allow additional people into the buildings. Please be understanding of our process and talk to your child about it before arriving on his/her LEAP day. Below is the bell schedule for the year as well as the LEAP days. #345Marlboro

In an effort to keep our students and our staff safe, starting August 24th, only the child will be allowed into the school. We will have staff available at the entrance to escort/direct your child to his/her classroom. We understand this is not the ideal situation and we wish we didn't have to put these procedures into practice, but due to the spread of COVID-19, we do not want to allow additional people into the buildings. Please be understanding of our process and talk to your child about it before arriving on his/her LEAP day. Below is the bell schedule for the year as well as the LEAP days. #345Marlboro

shared_text:
Roger Adkins
August 11 at 12:41 PM ·

Awesome tips for accessibility in this remote-learning era. Share, download, save!

Also: These steps help everyone!! A colleague today mentioned how, in two sections of the same course offered in the same semester several years ago, one section had a sort of closed captioning for one deaf student in the class (on a reader-board above the chalkboard), while the other did not have it. In the class with the captioning, the average student grade for all students was one full letter higher.

EDIT: Someone was kind enough to send me the original source for these, and to let me know that I missed the one for people with anxiety (added in the comments). The source is: https://accessibility.blog.gov.uk/2016/09/02/dos-and-donts-on-designing-for-accessibility/?fbclid=IwAR3w2CHNOwvnbduSBvafETl-MpHPaQNBOuM3Gpw-qDBaNfhGadL9oCz8pj4

post_text:
Most people experience at least one life changing event that they consider to be frightening or traumatic before becoming an adult.
When our children experience an event that they feel is traumatic - it can change the way they think, behave, and see the world around them.
Here is a short video to help you recognize childhood trauma and how to support your child from home:
"What is Childhood Trauma"
https://youtu.be/3UkODKVYdYo
A prize will be given to the first two (2) parents from every school who view and answers these two (2) questions:
1.) What is the role of the School Social Worker?
2.) How might traumatic experiences change the way your child thinks, behaves and understands the world around them?
Responses can be emailed to SW@marlboro.k12.sc.us.
You can contact your School Social Worker at (843) 631-7721, if you have questions.
#345
I Love You. I Care About You. I Am Here For You.
As always,
Thanks for your participation!
MCSD Social Work Team

post_text: Let’s show our 2020 Graduates just how much they mean to us! See you there! #345Marlboro
shared_text:
Marlboro County High School
June 2 at 7:17 PM ·

Attention Class of 2020:
On Saturday, June 6, 2020, the graduating class of 2020 will participate in a graduation parade at 9:00 am. We will start the line-up for the students in the back student parking lot of the school at 8:00 am. The parade will leave the school, making a right onto Tyson Ave, left on East Main St, left on Broad St and left on Fayetteville Ave to disperse.

Seniors are asked to wear their cap and gown and make signs for their vehicles. We are asking that everyone who participates drive safely on the parade route. Seniors you are welcome to drive yourself or have someone drive you. We do ask that only seniors and the driver who does not have to be a senior be in the vehicle.

We are encouraging the community to come out and celebrate our Class of 2020.

post_text:
RRI Undergraduate Loan Forgiveness Program

The Undergraduate Loan Forgiveness Program is available to all classroom teachers in the MCSD. The Program is funded by the Rural Teacher Recruitment and Retention Initiative (RRI) pursuant to FY20 Proviso 1A.54 funds.

The Program gives classroom teachers the opportunity to apply for up to $5,000 to be used to help pay down undergraduate loan balances.

For additional information visit http://www.marlboro.k12.sc.us/news/rural_undergraduate_loan_forgiveness_program

WANT TO WIN $25??

"How COVID-19 Has Affected Me Challenge"

Superintendent Dr. Gregory McCord will explain to you what you need to do to join the challenge and what you have a chance to win. The instructions below will complete the rest of the information:
A. To register and upload, go to https://mcsd345.com
To vote, go to https://mcsd345.com/vote/
To see the winners each day, starting Monday, May 4, go to
https://mcsd345.com/live
B. Be creative and be sure to share
C. You may submit only one entry per week.
D. Entries may be submitted Friday at 7 p.m. through
Tuesday at 11 p.m.
E. You may vote only once each day.
F. Voting opens each day at 6 a.m. and closes at 11 p.m.
G. Entries will be displayed on a first-come, first-served basis. The sooner you get your entry submitted, the more likely it will be at the top of the voting page.

Note: All entries will be vetted before publication. Submitting an entry gives us permission to post.

$25 winners will be chosen daily unless otherwise specified. #345Marlboro

Lights at the football stadium, baseball and softball fields will be turned on by coaches from 8:20-8:40 PM. This is 20:20 in military time. Students, parents, and fans are welcome to attend, but must stay in their vehicles to adhere to safeguards and social distancing during this time.

Thanks in advance!

post_text:
The 2020 South Carolina Boeing STEM Signing Day took place as a virtual event on April 23 at 10:30am EDT. STEM Signing Day celebrates high school seniors from across South Carolina who choose to pursue STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics) education at technical programs, two- and four-year colleges and universities. Just like signing days for athletes, STEM Signing Day honorees sign a letter of intent to pursue their STEM goals. #345Marlboro

Check back for a video of both honorees!

ALTERNATIVE TEACHER CERTIFICATION AVAILABLE THROUGH USC

Marlboro County School District has partnered with the University of South Carolina to participate in a new alternative certification, Carolina Collaborative for Alternative Preparation (CarolinaCAP). CarolinaCAP is part of a unique partnership developed by the University of South Carolina in partnership with the Center for Teaching Quality and partnering school districts. CarolinaCAP is a non-degree program leading to full licensure as teacher.

Join us on Wednesday, April 8th from 2pm – 3pm for the CarolinaCAP recruitment webinar. During this informative session, participants will learn more about:
• program partners,
• program design,
• admission requirements,
• application process, and
• program costs.

Click on the following link to register for the event: https://forms.gle/3tDaoZDkE9fQWSTu9. The webinar link will be sent to participants once registration is confirmed.

District contact Barbara McCall bmccall@marlboro.k12.sc.us
#345Marlboro

ATTENTION MCHS SENIORS

A drive-thru grad product delivery event has been scheduled for Thursday, April 2nd at 10:00-2:00

For the safety of all involved and to keep this event as efficient as possible, please follow the steps below:

1. All orders must be paid in full prior to the delivery day. If you have a balance, please pay online at RhodesGraduation.com.

2. Arrive at your appointed pick up time and follow the designated signs when you arrive at your school. They will be located in the parking lot at the front of the school.

10:00-11:00 Last Names A-F

11:00-12:00 Last Names G-L

12:00-1:00 Last Names M-R

1:00-2:00 Last Names S-Z

3. Stay in your vehicle and provide the delivery team your student name along with ID. MCHS administrators and faculty will be there for assistance.

4. Once you receive your graduation items, you will also receive an information card with how to contact Rhodes Graduation Services and Josten for additional questions or concerns.

Congratulations on this huge milestone! #345Marlboro

South Carolina Department of Education
March 26 at 3:39 PM ·

Please take a moment to read an important message from our partners at the South Carolina Department of Social Services.

Adjusting to life changes in response to COVID-19 may be overwhelming for children and adults. While families across South Carolina are doing the best they can to cope with school and workplace closings, we know that stressors like lost income, lack of child care, food insecurity, less access to healthcare and other resources, along with separation from social support systems, can take an emotional toll.

Please call 888-CARE4US (888-227-3487) if you witness or suspect a situation that threatens the safety and well-being of a child or vulnerable adult. SCDSS and other agencies are poised to help families remain stable and strong during this tough time.

South Carolina Department of Education
March 30 at 3:38 PM ·

📣 Important Information for Educators with Certificates Expiring June 30, 2020 📣

A one-year grace period will be added to all Initial, Professional, and Limited Professional certificates set to expire on June 30, 2020—including certificates that were extended for the 2019-20 school year. The new end-validity date will be June 30, 2021. Any extension already issued for the 2020-21 school year will be treated as a grace year and not counted as an extension.

Please note that the grace year will be added through an automated process.

The period for earning renewal credits will be extended to include the grace year, and renewal credits already earned will be applied to the renewal. Educators who have already earned their 120 renewal credits do not have to complete additional credits.

shared_text:
Marlboro County Government
March 22 at 5:56 PM ·

Marlboro County COVID-19 (Coronavirus) UPDATE 3-22.2020

SCDHEC advises that there is NOT A CONFIRMED CASE of COVID-19 in Marlboro County.

Marlboro County officials were advised this afternoon by SCDHEC that the agency mistakenly identified a positive test result as a Marlboro County resident.

James Buckner, the Public Health Director for DHEC's Pee Dee Region, wrote in an email to county officials, "Marlboro County does not have a case of COVID19 in the county. Upon further investigation into this case DHEC staff discovered the person tested was not a Marlboro County resident. . . We apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused you. "

Marlboro County officials have expressed their displeasure with SCDHEC regarding this incident as well as poor communication with local governments from the agency. SC DHEC is responsible for the accuracy of information released to the County and to the public.

Marlboro County Emergency Management will provide additional updates as they become available.

This information was sent by Lead Media Specialist from Marlboro County High School, Teresa Reid.

If your students need reading materials for book reports, projects, etc., please share this information with them. The Media Center has a collection of eBooks, primarily fiction, that can be checked out using the students' Destiny accounts. The link to the instructional brochure is below and may be shared via your Google Classrooms. The students' usernames are their PS numbers (printed on IDs), and their passwords are the same passwords they use to access grades/attendance in PS.

The eBooks may be accessed via any device with internet access including their Chromebooks.

Destiny Discover Brochure Link: https://drive.google.com/open?id=1rxHp07Ps9BOi8eqgp4qr6mCs1tdwQhfB

post_text:
Good afternoon,
Effective immediately all schools will be closed for a period of 14 days. Please continue to check our website as we will update information twice daily. This will include our plans for the distribution of lunches as well as how you may be able to contact us. Essential staff (front office staff, custodians, cafeteria staff, bus drivers, district level staff, and senior staff) will be asked to report on regular schedule. Cafeteria staff will report to MCHS at 7 (other essential staff will report to their regular locations at regular time). Bus regular routes will be running with a 5 hour delay, delivering lunch, not picking up students. All children under 18 years of age will be eligible for the free meal. If children miss the bus meal delivery, meals can also be picked up at schools in a drive through setting from 11am – 12pm.

This is an unknow time for each of us therefore we are asking everyone to remain calm, patient and understanding as we work through this together. #345Marlboro

post_text: College and career ready! #345Marlboro
shared_text:
Northeastern Technical College added 152 new photos to the album: NETC on the Road at Marlboro County High School — at Marlboro County High.
March 10 at 3:10 PM · Bennettsville, SC ·

Northeastern Technical College (NETC) went on the road to talk to Seniors about their plans following graduation. Marlboro County High School hosted NETC Day on Friday, February 21, in the high school media center. 50 NETC employees met with high school seniors to help them explore educational opportunities at the college. Over 200 Seniors attended NETC Day, and 84 committed to complete academic programs and degrees at NETC.

shared_text:
Marlboro County High School
February 24 at 7:13 PM ·

Good evening,

Our Marlboro County Boys basketball Team will travel to Columbia to play AC Flora in round 3 of the playoffs, tomorrow, February 25, 2020. Gates will open at 5:30 PM but we encourage you to arrive early as we expect the gym to be near capacity by 6:30 PM. Please be reminded of the clear bag and security gate policies that will be in effect. Let's come out and support our Mighty Bulldogs.

Students who will traveling with the school should pay for their ticket ($6.00) and turn in their permission slips by 8:30 in the morning in the cafeteria. Students must show ID when purchasing a ticket. Permission slips should include a parent/guardian signature and contact number. Dress code is the same as the school's dress code. Students should have money for food as well. Students are expected to be on their best behavior. School rules still apply.

post_text: Marlboro County Boys Basketball finished the regular season as Region 6 AAAA champs. All five starters were named to All Region. Wesley Brown, DreVeon Scott, and Devonta Oliver were all named to First Team All Region. Ryan Dupree was named 2nd Team and Jamiek McCoy was named to third team. Coach Brace was also named Coach of the Year for Region 6 AAAA. Bulldogs won first round of playoffs against Orangeburg-Wilkerson 62-50 and will host Darlington on Saturday at 7. #345Marlboro

post_text: Marlboro County School district pre-kindergarten teachers and paraprofessionals attended the South Carolina Early Childhood Association conference in Charleston, SC this past Thursday-Saturday. While at the conference, the Bennettsville Primary teachers attended a class called, Be An Astronaut. This class was intended to help teacher’s produce more rigorous science activities that are hands-on. During one of the activities, the teachers had to create an astronaut outfit. BPS created their astronaut suits and decided to try them out! #345Marlboro

post_text:
Marlboro County School District is launching the STOPit Solutions program. This program will allow students and parents the ability to anonymously send in reports of serious incidents which could include: Bullying, Cyberbullying, Harassment, Violence, Alcohol/Drug related issues, etc.

While this program will mainly address middle and high school ages, we are making it available to all parents in the district. The STOPit app is a free download from iTunes or Google Play. The Access Code for the District is: #345MCSD. Once you get log in, you can tab which school you need to report an incident to. The school administrators will receive the information, investigate the situation and follow through as necessary.

Now students will have options available to help with eradicating bullying for all. We hope to change the culture to one of acceptance in this community with this new app.

If you have any questions or we can be of any assistance, please call any school and ask to speak to an administrator. #345Marlboro

post_text:
We are so happy and proud to announce Mr. Michael Baker of McColl Elementary Middle School was selected as Marlboro County School District Employee of the Month! He was recognized at last night's School Board Meeting and presented a plaque and a gift certificate to Breeden's Grocery! Here is what was written about Mr. Baker that clinched this honor for him:

Mr. Baker is the epitome of a team player. He is considerate of everyone around him – team members and other staff members alike. He is the first to step up and volunteer for extra duties, such as walking with the band in the Christmas parade and assisting the Academic Challenge Team, as well as attends more athletic events than is required by the school. Mr. Baker is brand new to teaching but has shown to be an eager and coachable teacher. He is always seeking direction and guidance from Administration and coaches and teachers on his hallway to improve his craft. He also steps into student situations to support teachers or administration without prompting.

Congratulations Mr. Baker! #345Marlboro
